No School for Students on March 16, 2020

Monday March 16, 2020, is being designated as a staff development day, to allow our staff extra time to prepare on-line learning opportunities for our students should the district have to close school for an extended period of time. Students will not report to school on Monday. If there is any change in regard to this plan, the Superintendent will contact the community over the weekend.

post_text: Mount Sinai’s Ocean science Bowl team won the New York Regional Bay Scallop bowl at StonyBrook University on Saturday, Feb., 1st. The NYS champions were led by Arielle Mule’, Aaron Angress, Jonathon Jacobson, Katherine Fedotov and Matthew Miller. We had a tough morning going 1-2 and were seeded #10 out of the 12 teams that were there but fought our way back in the afternoon and finally beat Midwood High school from the Bronx to win the title. The team will now head to Mississippi in April to compete in the National Ocean Science Bowl tournament against the best teams around the country.
text: Mount Sinai’s Ocean science Bowl team won the New York Regional Bay Scallop bowl at StonyBrook University on Saturday, Feb., 1st. The NYS champions were led by Arielle Mule’, Aaron Angress, Jonathon Jacobson, Katherine Fedotov and Matthew Miller. We had a tough morning going 1-2 and were seeded #10 out of the 12 teams that were there but fought our way back in the afternoon and finally beat Midwood High school from the Bronx to win the title. The team will now head to Mississippi in April to compete in the National Ocean Science Bowl tournament against the best teams around the country.

post_text:
Dear Mrs. Rickert,

I wanted to thank you and all of your students for taking the time out of your school day to write us these motivating letters. It is because of the support from the people back home that helps get the troops through these deployments. The letters from your students inspire the men and women who read them. Knowing that the children are aware of the world’s changing situations and the support our country gives to our allies overseas is important. The letters and the drawings we received were sincerely appreciated. Our men and women can accomplish the mission better every day knowing that we have the support of our families, friends and fellow community members.

Thank you again for your support.

GOD BLESS AMERICA

BRIAN K. CAVANAGH, MSGT, USAF
Deputy Fire Chief
407th Fire and Emergency Service
Ahmed Al-Jabber Air Base

Hour of Code at Mount Sinai School District
This December students from all over the world will take part in the Hour of Code. Held during Computer Science Education week, this international movement supports the idea of young students learning to program. This year all Mount Sinai students in grades K-6 will be participating in the Hour of Code during their library time, while 7th and 8th graders will explore coding in their Computers 7 & 8 class. During the Hour of Code, students will play fun computer games while learning the fundamentals of computer science. This is a great way to introduce students to Computer Science basics and spark an interest in creating with technology rather than just consuming.

https://hourofcode.com/us/en/images/hour-of-code-logo.png

post_text: In order to promote the health and safety of students and staff, please be aware that High School student drop off/pick up will be along the north side of the HS parking lot. Once a student is dropped off or picked up, parents will be directed to exit via the North West exit behind the HS. Only students and staff that have the appropriate credentials will be permitted to enter the HS parking lot during arrival and dismissal. There will be staff located in various locations to assist you while we pilot this initiative. We always encourage students to use school transportation, however if you must drop off/pick up your child, please see the map attached for further clarification of this new procedure. Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation.

post_text:
Remembrance Vigil for Principal Robert Grable:

Please join staff , students , your Mount Sinai neighbors and friends to honor and remember our beloved Principal as a Community on:

July 22 7-8:00 pm in front of Mount Sinai High School (rain or shine)

The North Country Road entrance will be closed as will the High School parking lot . the parking lot will be open to pedestrian traffic only. Parking will be in the Middle School and Elementary School parking lots and over flow areas (All gates will be open at the close of the vigil to exit Access to the High School parking lot will remain closed at the barn)

We will be taking Donations by check to establish the Rob Grable’s daughters Scholarship Fund Please make your donation check out to the Mount Sinai Administrators Association who will create the scholarship you may mail a check to the District Office if you wish as well attention Mount Sinai Administrators Association

Thank you all who will be able to join us and all who join us in spirit and prayer

Parking will be in the Middle School and Elementary School parking lots and over flow areas (All gates will be open at the close of the vigil to exit Access to the High School parking lot will remain closed at the barn)

Thank you all who will be able to join us and all who join us in spirit and prayer

Mount Sinai School District

post_text:
Kenneth Wei finished the weekend with 5 gold medals and 1 bronze medal. Having one of the most successful state meets in history.

Triple Jump- State champion 3rd in the federation.

110 Hurdles- State and federation champion.

Long Jump- State and federation champion

The Girls team scored 58 points to become the best D2 public school in New York State!
Kayleigh Robinson ran the 5th best time in the 100mHH and was the repeating state champion in the 400mIH.
Sarah Connelly was the repeating state champion in the 3000m race and was the state and federation champion in 1500m race.

Congratulations to the girls track team members that competed in the State Meet.
The team scored 58 points to become the best D2 public school in New York State!
The 4x400m relay team placed 2nd with Catherine Carillo, Aristea Franks, Kyra Franks and Kayleigh Robinson.
The 4x800m relay team placed 3rd with Isabella DiPalermo, Heather Caputo, Sarah Connelly and Kaitlyn Chandrika.
Individual Events:
Kate DelGandio placed 11th in the 100mHH.
Kaitlyn Chandrika 10 in the 2000m Steeple Chase.
Sarah Gunasekera placed 11th in the Long Jump and 4th in the Triple Jump.
Anastasia Richards placed 2nd in the Discus and 7th in the federation.
Kyra Franks placed 5th in the 400m race.
Kayleigh Robinson ran the 5th best time in the 100mHH and was the repeating state champion in the 400mIH.
Sarah Connelly was the repeating state champion in the 3000m race and was the state and federation champion in 1500m race.

The 4×400 placed 16th with Tommy Grolz, Jackson Law, Mario Xerri and Ryan Wilson.

The 4×100 placed 9th with Shane Bombace, Matty LoMonaco, Neil Esposito and Hunter Tegay.

The 4x 800 placed 8th with Christian Law, Mario Xerri, Sean Higgins and Ryan Wilson.

The winners of the 2018 middle school science fair who scored “Best in Show” brought their research projects to the Long Island Science Congress Regional Science Fair on April 9 to compete with students from across Long Island. Participants presented their projects to three judges the results of which will be received in early May.

Students conducted their research in seventh grade under the guidance of Mrs. Anderson, Mr. Joyce and Mr. Foster. Mr. Joyce and Mrs. Anderson accompanied the student’s to the LISC and also were judges for the day. I am looking forward to sharing the scores in May.

The attendees from left to right in the picture attached above are:

Lily Rubenstein, Katie Kit, Aria Reilly, Kate Rubino, Ryan Gross, Christian Hedlund, Andrew Colle, Michael Graffeo, Lawrence Cao, Joseph Colucci, and Lucas Code.

post_text:
Members of the boys and girls basketball teams ran a benefit clinic for Friends of Karen, a local children’s charity that assists families of children with life threatening illnesses. The team ran drills, stations and different fun competitions for the kids in attendance.

The teams were able to raise $750 from the event. All proceeds from the clinic went to the charity

Here is a little about "FRIENDS OF KAREN"

Vision
Every child with a life-threatening illness, and his or her family, will have all that they need to keep them stable, functioning and able to cope.
Mission
Provide emotional, financial and advocacy support for children with a life-threatening illness and their families in order to help keep them stable, functioning, and able to cope.

We started in 1978 with one family; one child, Karen MacInnes; and one inspired woman, Sheila Petersen. Since then, we have assisted nearly 15,000 children and their families.
